article.description: Alana Beard had 22 points Sunday and Duke (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 1 AP) used a late run to beat No. 13 North Carolina 79-57 for the Blue Devils' 500th victory.
article.headline: Beard paces Blue Devils with 22 points
article.linkText: Duke routs North Carolina for 500th victory
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- After 33 tough minutes against its in-state
rival, Duke (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 1 AP) turned up its defensive intensity. The result was
another victory in an impressive Atlantic Coast Conference winning
streak.

Alana Beard had 22 points Sunday and the Blue Devils used a late
run to beat No. 13 North Carolina 79-57 for their 500th victory.

Mistie Bass scored 18 points for the Blue Devils (13-1, 4-0
ACC), who improved to 500-300 in the program's 29 seasons. Monique
Currie added 14 points and 15 rebounds for Duke, which has won 47
straight conference games.

Duke has not lost an ACC game since falling to North Carolina
State 69-55 in February 2001.

Duke also improved to 23-1 as the nation's top-ranked team,
while the Tar Heels (13-2, 3-1) fell to 0-18 against No. 1 teams.

"We weathered the storm, stayed together and really made some
runs ourselves," Duke coach Gail Goestenkors said.

Duke had won the last two meetings here by 20 and 34 points, but
the Tar Heels stayed with the Blue Devils most of the way Sunday.
The Blue Devils scored 16 straight points late, shutting down the
Tar Heels and getting strong play from Bass inside, to put the game
out of reach.

During that run, Duke held the Tar Heels without a field goal
for the final 7:51. Duke scored 25 of the game's final 28 points
and held the Tar Heels to a season-low 29 percent shooting.

Duke finished with 12 steals and 10 blocked shots.

"Anytime you want to go on a run, you've got to get defensive
stops," Beard said. "We stepped up our intensity and we just shut
them down in the last minutes."

It was a disappointing loss for the Tar Heels, who have not won
at Cameron Indoor Stadium since January 1997. North Carolina has
lost 10 straight and 13 of 14 to Duke.

"I just think we gave up at the end," said freshman Ivory
Latta, who had 17 points to lead the Tar Heels. "From now on, we
just need to play the whole 40 minutes instead of playing 34 or 35
minutes, because that's not going to help us out at all."

Latta and Camille Little combined for 11 points during a 21-10
run to open the second half, erasing a 38-27 halftime deficit and
tying it at 48 with about 10 minutes left. But the Blue Devils went
ahead to stay when Beard found Lindsey Harding for a 3-pointer and
a 57-54 lead with 6:40 left.

That ignited the 16-0 run, with Bass scoring six points by
getting to the free throw line and crashing the boards. She went
3-for-4 at the line and kept a possession alive that led to a
basket inside by Iciss Tillis.

Bass then grabbed an offensive rebound on a missed free throw by
Harding and completed a three-point play for a 68-54 lead.

"That's my game: I like to scrap around," Bass said. "It just
makes it even better to go in and go for the rebounds. ... It just
makes it a better experience to know you came out on top and that
you worked to get there."

Duke took a 50-40 edge on the glass and pulled down 16 offensive
boards in a physical game that featured 37 personal fouls and 45
free throws between the teams.

"We need to bring the football team in and scrimmage against
them a little bit so we'll be ready for the next time we play,"
North Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell said.
